November through March brings Vancouver Island's most violent weather. Storm-force winds (60+ km/h), heavy rain, and coastal surge can damage homes fast. By the time a storm arrives, it's too late to prepare. This is your checklist.

## Inspect Your Roof

**What to check:**
- Shingles for curling, cracking, or missing pieces
- Flashing around vents, chimneys, and skylights (should lay flat and sealed)
- Gutters for debris and damage
- Fascia for rot or damage

**What to fix:**
- Replace or re-nail loose shingles
- Re-seal flashing with roofing cement if water is dripping
- Clear gutters completely
- Replace rotted fascia

**Why it matters:** High winds lift shingles, exposing the wood underneath. Once exposed, water runs into the attic, rots the structure, and causes mold. A $200 shingle repair now beats a $10,000 roof leak later.

**Don't DIY this.** Roof work is dangerous and requires expertise. Call a roofer or experienced handyman.

## Secure Your Chimney and Vents

**What to check:**
- Chimney cap (should be secure and uncracked)
- Roof vents (should be screwed tight)
- Exhaust ducts (should be sealed to the roof)
- Flashing around each penetration

**What to fix:**
- Tighten all fasteners
- Replace cracked caps
- Re-seal any gaps with roofing cement

**Why it matters:** Wind pressure and rain can force water through vents and flashing. A loose chimney cap lets rain straight down the flue.

## Trim Tree Branches

**What to do:**
- Trim any branches overhanging your roof (6+ feet above ground)
- Remove dead wood or branches that look weak
- Clear branches from gutters and vents
- Thin trees to reduce wind resistance

**Why it matters:** Heavy, wet snow and high winds break branches. A branch through your roof is expensive. Falling branches damage siding, gutters, and cars.

**Call a pro if:** Branches are large, high, or near power lines. An arborist has the right equipment and insurance.

## Inspect and Repair Siding

**What to check:**
- Cracks or gaps in wood or vinyl siding
- Missing or damaged caulk around windows and doors
- Wood siding for soft spots or rot
- Paint or stain condition (especially on exposed areas)

**What to fix:**
- Caulk gaps and cracks (exterior caulk, not interior)
- Replace damaged siding
- Repair or paint wood siding
- Tighten any loose boards

**Why it matters:** Small gaps become water entry points. Wind-driven rain exploits cracks and forces water into walls, causing hidden rot and mold.

## Secure Gutters and Downspouts

**What to check:**
- Gutters for debris, sagging, or damage
- Downspout connections (should be tight)
- Downspout extensions (should drain away from the foundation, 4+ feet)
- Fasteners and supports

**What to fix:**
- Clean gutters completely
- Tighten or re-nail sagging sections
- Extend downspouts if water is pooling at the foundation
- Secure any loose downspouts

**Why it matters:** Heavy rain in a storm loads gutters with water. Sagging gutters overflow, water runs down the fascia, and it pools at the foundation. That causes basement leaks and foundation damage.

## Check Your Deck and Railings

**What to check:**
- Railing connections (should be solid, not wiggling)
- Deck boards for soft wood or rot
- Ledger bolts (should be tight)
- Loose fasteners throughout

**What to fix:**
- Tighten all railing bolts and fasteners
- Replace soft or rotten boards
- Re-secure ledger if it's pulling away
- Tighten any loose bolts or fasteners

**Why it matters:** Wind pushes on railings. A loose railing fails and someone gets hurt. A storm can blow a weakened deck railing clean off.

## Inspect Window and Door Seals

**What to check:**
- Caulk around windows and doors (should be intact, not cracked)
- Weatherstripping (should be compressed, not flat or missing)
- Window frames for rot or soft wood
- Locks and latches (should operate smoothly)

**What to fix:**
- Remove old caulk and re-caulk gaps
- Replace compressed or missing weatherstripping
- Repair soft wood or rotted frames
- Tighten hinges and latches

**Why it matters:** Wind-driven rain exploits gaps. Water forces its way in around windows and doors. It runs behind the frame and rots the sill and frame wood.

## Check for Tree or Branch Issues

**What to look for:**
- Dead limbs (gray, no bark)
- Large limbs hanging over the house
- Trees growing too close to the roof
- Weak connections (limbs splitting from the trunk)

**What to do:**
- Call an arborist to assess large trees
- Trim branches yourself if they're small and safe
- Remove dead trees if they're near your house

**Why it matters:** Winter storms combined with wet snow add weight to branches. Loaded branches break and fall on roofs, cars, and power lines.

## Prepare Emergency Supplies

Even if your home is storm-ready, be prepared for outages:
- Flashlights and extra batteries
- Candles and matches
- First aid kit
- Medications (especially any requiring refrigeration)
- Canned food and manual can opener
- Drinking water (1 gallon per person per day, 3-day supply minimum)
- Battery-powered radio
- Full phone charges

## After a Storm

- Document damage with photos
- Don't enter roof/dangerous areas to assess damage
- Call a contractor or handyman if you suspect damage
- Contact your insurance company quickly
- Keep receipts for emergency repairs

## Timing

**September–October:** Inspect roof, chimney, and major structures. Fix now before storms.

**October–November:** Trim trees, secure gutters, seal windows and doors.

**November–February:** Monitor after storms. Check for new damage. Clear debris.

**March:** Final inspection after winter. Assess what held and what failed.

## Bottom Line

Preparation is cheap insurance. A few hundred dollars spent now prevents thousands in damage. If you're unsure about anything, call a pro for an inspection. Storm damage is fast and expensive. Prevention is worth every dollar.

